  <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">where 
   <span class="italic">r</span> is the hydrodynamic radius (Henriksen and Hansen, 
   <a rid="B43" ref-type="bibr" href="#B43">2008</a>). This treatment of course does not provide further insight into these amply investigated issues, but points at a simple and perhaps useful physical interpretation of a long-standing as well recent intriguing rate phenomena. From a general perspective, the theory encourages considering wide ranges of available data on geochemistry (Giordano and Russell, 
   <a rid="B39" ref-type="bibr" href="#B39">2018</a>), supercooled liquids science (Angell, 
   <a rid="B2" ref-type="bibr" href="#B2">1995</a>) and biochemistry (Kohen et al., 
   <a rid="B51" ref-type="bibr" href="#B51">1999</a>) and digging for hidden insights. Preliminary searches, to be published, turned on successful.
